node.text:
Homemade sourdough bagels are the b.e.s.t!!! 🤤🥯🥰 Swipe over for video tutorials showing my process - posted in reverse order! 😃 Biggest tips: use a high gluten flour for that traditional chewy texture, and make sure to keep your dough hydration very low -- I'm around 60% hydration for this particular blend of flour, and I'll post the recipe details below. Topped with everything seasoning or black sesame seeds. Had these for dinner last night with ham and cream cheese 🤩 Simply delicious!

Recipe notes:
Use a very active, not overly ripe starter. I supplemented with diastatic malt powder as neither of my flours contained it, as I like the added browning it causes. You can use whatever flour you have, just keep care to not over-hydrate. Adding lye to the simmering water is optional! See my previous bagel posts for bulk ferment variations (search "bagels" using the link in my bio)!

In a mixer, knead together on low speed for 10 minutes: 30g levain + 330g water + 18g barley malt syrup + 575g flour (blend of @centralmilling 350g ABC- + 225g High Mountain) + 4g diastatic malt + 11g salt + 20g caster sugar.
Room temp bulk 6 hours at ~78°F with 2 coil folds (fold every 3 hours).
Transfer to fridge overnight.
Pull out of fridge in the morning, then divide into 8 pieces (~120g each) and round into balls. Rest at 78°F 1.5 hrs.
Shape as you see in video here, then transfer to semolina-dusted couche or towel. Cover and final proof 1.5 hrs 78°F.
Preheat oven to 500°F 1 hr with stone.
Simmer 2kg water + 11g barley malt syrup + 3.5g lye.
Boil 2-4 bagels at a time, 40 sec per side. Top with seeds as in video. Transfer to parchment lined baking sheet.
Bake 25-28 min at lowered 425°F or until bagels are nicely browned. Cool a bit then serve!! ❤️😋

Thanks as always to @maurizio and @amyduska for the bagel tips!! 🙏

node.text:
Red quinoa with porcini mushroom and rosemary -- woodsy, savory, absolutely delicious with great texture!! 😃🤤 Easy enough to make using your favorite flour/water blend - I used a mix of 15% @palouse_brand hard red spring wheat and 85% @bobsredmill artisan bread flour at 85% hydration. Sprinkled on the inclusions and powder during a lamination stage, and after a few coils I shaped and proofed and baked! Oh my goodness the aromas wafting through my kitchen were incredible during the bake, and what an outstanding flavor. This is a keeper!!! Hope you try it...! 😍🤗

Recipe notes:
Autolysed 2 hours: 275g flour blend (45g whole wheat + 235g bread flour) + 225g water - mixed using a mixer with paddle, 2 min on low speed.
Added 10% levain (usually I add 20% but I only had 30g to use for this bake!) 🤭
30 min later added the 6g salt. Salt and levain were added by hand.
Laminated as you see in the video if you swipe over, and then performed 3 coils throughout bulk to build up the strength of the dough.
Shaped taut dough using #noshaping method (see my recent previous posts for video) after a 7.5 hour bulk (dough was nice and puffy!).
Proofed overnight at 38°F, then baked next morning using @challengerbreadware pan as usual!

Please see the link in my bio for all of my notes on baking setup, and every part of the method I like to use to make a basic loaf of sourdough bread 🌾🥰👍

node.text:
Apple cinnamon blue swirl -- ok ok this is a good bread. It's the first time I've incorporated apple and I was hoping for even more bold flavor!! Each bite with the lightly dehydrated apple is a delicious one, and of course the cinnamon pairs magnificently... But I think next time I'm going to be adding in a touch of cider and maybe butter as well! 😃 The blue swirl is just for fun 😂💙 half the dough was hydrated using a very concentrated steeped tea using dry butterfly pea flowers 🦋 I'll be recreating this bake again soon - helps me to get into the fall season 🥰

If you have tips your can share in making a super apple-y bread, please leave a comment!! 🙏🤗

Quick notes:
Autolysed 2 hours:
Dough A (25g @jovialfoods einkorn + 125g @bobsredmill ABF + 120g water).
Dough B: (150g flour blend as above + 120g steeped water) **6g separated flower tops + 130g just off the boil water, steeped 10 min then drained and cooled before using.
20% levain, 2.1% salt.
Added 70g diced apples during Lamination stage (swipe over for video). **Cut granny Smith apples 1/4" thick and partially dehydrated in oven at 200°F 1 hour.
1 coil fold a couple hours later, then shaped at 6.5 hour mark (75°F).
Final proofed in banneton at 45°F overnight.
Baked as usual in @challengerbreadware pan.

Please see the link in my bio for more tips about every part of the methods I love to use to make sourdough! 💙💚

node.text:
Roasted red pepper and smoked Gouda 🧡 Just like last time, smoky and cheesy: what a loaf to savor!! 🤤 Use your favorite blend of flour 🌾 and plan to reduce your usual hydration a touch 💦 so that you can fold in some red pepper puree (which carries with it a lot of water). I spread it on after allowing a little time for the gluten network to develop (I wait until after adding the salt) and then handle the dough very delicately so I don't turn it into a puddle of a disintegrated mess. The shredded cheese was added for even distribution during the lamination folding stage 👌🔥😁 Hope you enjoy!

Quick notes:
2 hour autolyse. 12% @palouse_brand hard red spring wheat + 88% @bobsredmill ABF strong flour. 74% hydration. 20% levain and 2.2% sea salt. Divided dough, added 10g water to one dough to reach desired hydration/dough feel. Added 36g roasted red pepper puree to second dough as in video here.
After a long rest to relax the doughs, laminated them together again with 50g fresh shredded smoked Gouda (also try with fontina it's outstanding!).
1/2 coils rest of bulk when needed. Into banneton (#noshaping technique as the dough was so tight) at 6.5 hrs (75°F) and proofed overnight at 38°F.
Baked in @challengerbreadware pan as usual.
Please see link in my IG bio for tips on Baker's Math, how to fully activate your levain, and full tutorials on how to make a basic loaf of sourdough bread 🌾🥰🙏

node.text:
Turmeric pairs pretty beautifully with porcini mushroom I must say! 🍄 Very earthy and rich - and together with the warm turmeric it's just 👌😋 I made some amazing Bolognese sauce a week ago and had some extra porcini powder on hand 😍🔥 Glad to incorporate it into some bread - more recipes to come!!

I incorporated by sprinkling the mushroom powder onto the dough during the lamination stage when I went to combine my two split doughs (swipe over for Video showing this step). You don't have to split your doughs, but again I really enjoy the depth of marbled color with splitting, and I also notice a more open crumb structure when I do this as well (likely from the high integrity white dough that lacks the turmeric powder laced through). 

You can find the porcini powder I used on my Baking Supplies page (see link in my bio) and the turmeric powder is by @srisritattva 💛💛

Recipe notes:
Autolysed doughs for 2 hours: Dough A (25g @jovialfoods einkorn + 125g @bobsredmill ABF + 120g water); Dough B (150g flour blend as above + 2g turmeric powder + 120g water).
Added to each dough 30g levain, then 30 min later 3.5g sea salt.
90 min later, laminated out the two doughs and added the porcini powder (swipe over for video). ~1/2 tablespoon worth.
1 coil fold 90 min later.
Shaped after a 6.5 hour bulk, however dough looked a little smaller in the banneton so instead of final proofing at 38°F I final proofed at 45°F to get a little extra rise in the dough overnight.
Baked as usual using my @challengerbreadware pan. See the link in my bio and lots of resources showcasing all parts of my methods! 🥰🌾

node.text:
Totally thrilled with how these turned out! Braided brioche 100% sourdough - used a stiff sugar starter to leaven these. See my previous two posts for instructions on how to make the levain and dough and video tutorials on how to shape the ropes and how to braid. I learned the braiding technique from the wonderful Katharina @besondersgut who posts her tutorials online 🥰🤗🙏 These turned out so soft and tender with a pastry-like crust - absolutely heavenly flavor - rich and decadent from the enrichments 🤤

Off to see my parents today - I'll be gifting one of these to my dad as it's his birthday! The rest will go for French toast 👌 I shared with you my French toast recipe the last time I posted a 12-strand braided loaf (back on May 27th) but if you didn't catch it then, here it is again. You can thank me later 😅

Set thick cut slices out on the counter overnight covered with a tea towel. Next morning, whisk 2 egg yolks + 1 cup milk + 1/4 tsp vanilla extract + dash of cinnamon. Soak for 5-10 minutes, turning over a few times until the toast pieces are fully soaked through. Fry in a pat of butter on low heat for 5 minutes per side, or until they are nicely caramelized! Top with maple syrup and sliced berries! 😃🔥

node.text:
That beautiful stiff sugar levain from yesterday was used to make this incredibly lovely brioche dough (see recipe notes below)... I used the super helpful videos by my friend Katharina @besondersgut (check out her IG page! 😍) to create these braids: one is an 8-strand and one is a 5-strand. There's this sense of well-being that comes over me when I'm rolling out the individual strands and braiding these beauties.

I took video of the whole process if you wanted to swipe over -- how I roll out the mini logs, then after a rest how I roll them out to their full 12 inch length, and finally how I braid the breads (videos here are in reverse order) 💖 Each braid looks complicated but has a pattern that you learn as you perform them. The more you make the easier it becomes 😅

I'll post the final bread photos in just a bit!! 🔥🥰

Base dough recipe and notes: Makes 18 strands at ~65g each (I made 2x 5 stranded and 1x 8 stranded braids).
Be sure to use a very strong, well-refreshed starter (please check the link in my bio for full YouTube tutorial)!
Build stiff sugar levain ~3pm: 60g active starter + 150g bread flour + 60g water + 15g caster sugar. Knead on counter till nice and smooth. Cover, rest ~5 hrs until peaked at ~82°F. This kind of starter is a very powerful leavener for enriched doughs!!
In the bowl of a stand mixer, combo 240g levain, 4 cold egg yolks + 1 cold whole egg, 125g cool water, 80g caster (or granulated) sugar, 108g unsalted butter, 8g sea salt, and 540g @kingarthurbaking AP flour in mixer bowl. Knead on low 15 min with the dough hook.
Cool bulk overnight ~18°C/64°F until dough about doubles in volume (mine took ~11 hours!).
Divide into 18g pieces ~65g each, and shape into tight balls. Rest 60 min, covered with cling film, to relax the dough.
Roll out to fully degas with rolling pin into a rectangle and roll into short rope (see video). Rest 45 min, covered.
Roll out to a full ~12-14" length, lightly flour the strands, then braid the breads as in video.
Proof 4 hrs at 80-82°F until nice and puffed. Brush all over with egg wash (1 yolk + 1 Tbl water).
Bake at 400°F 15 min on a baking stone, then another 25-30 min at 350°F until nicely browned 🔥

#NoShaping! 😃 I work with some pretty strong bread flour, and generally need a high hydration (88-90% 💦) to keep my dough nice and extensible - if I happen to reduce the water (~84% 💦), then the result is a more stiff dough that requires maybe 1-2 coil folds throughout bulk! In this particular case, I tipped my dough out from the dish onto the counter to shape, and thought to myself that my usual shaping method would over-tighten the dough. So that's when I thought about my friend Pekka...!

Pekka @panedepain shared this #noshaping technique awhile back - he demonstrates how a normal coil fold, performed later in the bulk, can serve as the actual shaping... Then, after a short rest, he simply flips the dough straight from the dish right into the banneton! 😱😍👌 See his featured highlight on this subject!

In this video here I'm showing sort of an adaptation of this - and it can be used whenever I feel my dough is overly taut at the end of bulk (when it's either too low hydration, or I've done the final coil too late, or it's simply overly proofy). So if you ever do a coil on the later side and notice your dough seems sort of tight and you can't really get a great shaping out of it, try this super minimalist method!! 😁💛🌾

Dough is 30% semola flour, 70% @centralmilling Electra Light, 84% hydration. 2 coil folds throughout bulk (~75°F, 6.5 hrs). Pressed wood pulp banneton by @flourside_ 🙏 Followed Basic Method as seen in the link in my Insta bio! ❤️

node.text:
A back to basics loaf! 🌾🥰 For me, baking = joy. I can't seem to get enough of it.... The mixing of the various flour blends, the smell of the doughy mix, the way the dough develops and how it feels as it stretches out. Deciding what next inclusions to try out and observing how they affect the quality of the dough, taking notes. Watching the dough as it grows - becoming supple and smooth and puffy, full of millions of little air bubbles - it's alive!!! ❤️ That final moment too, pulling the lid off in the bake to see the bloom 🔥... Smelling that fresh warm bread smell every morning. The final slicing and slathering with butter or dipped in oil - oh man, I am totally hooked 😂 Happy baking everyone - and please read to the end for a very important message 🙏🤗

For this loaf, I stuck completely to my Basic Method (see the link in my bio and my full YouTube tutorial or pre-recorded workshop). Autolysed (2 hrs) 275g flour blend (30g fresh milled @meadowlark_organics wheat berries + 30g white @kamutbrand Kamut + 215g @bobsredmill artisan bread flour) + 235g water.
Hang mixed in the levain (55g), then the salt (6g).
3 coil folds throughout bulk. Shaped at ~75% total dough rise (6.5 hrs at ~75°F).
Overnight cold rest at 38°F. Baked next morning using @challengerbreadware pan as usual!

At the end here: I wanted to say a massive and very heartfelt THANK YOU 🙏🙏🙏 to everyone who sent in uplifting words and/or who ordered from my Shopify store this last few days. I cannot explain how much this means to me. This little business has sure taken me on an emotional roller coaster this last year and I am so happy to see product bring fulfilled at our warehouse and knowing jars and kits and starter are going out to bakers all around the world! Watching it all come together: It's unbelievable, really. Crazy amazing - I thank you so very much for your support, your enthusiasm, your generosity 🥰❤️🥰❤️🥰 Thank you, and happy baking!! I hope you all love your jars and starter as much as I love them!!
